  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Cold Food Festival
  author: Kim Heun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At Cold Food Festival, homeless and adrift,
    my heart and circumstances drift apart.
    The world's beauty remains, yet it is not my home—
    three thousand miles away, still I have not returned.

    In dreams the ancestral graves grow distant and dim,
    while in my sorrow the peach and plum blossoms bloom in full glory.
    Swings and kickball—I care for them not at all.
    Instead I compose new verses to bid farewell to the setting sun.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Cold Food Festival (Hansi) falls 105 days after the winter solstice, traditionally a time when families return home to tend ancestral graves. The poet's absence from this observance deepens the poem's melancholy.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'ancestral graves' (松楸) reference the Confucian duty of filial piety and ancestral veneration central to East Asian culture.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem contrasts the carefree pastimes of spring (swings and kickball) with the poet's solitary contemplation, suggesting a withdrawal into artistic expression as solace for displacement.
